D.3.c	  Operating Procedures

Standard operating procedures that are clearly written and current and safe work practices can ensure that both experienced and inexperienced employees operate the process and respond to emergencies in a safe, consistent, and prescribed manner. Such procedures benefit the release prevention program by providing operating personnel with clear and concise guidance to prevent and/or respond to an accidental release.  CCWD has developed a written operating procedures program, which satisfies the requirements of Section 2755.3 of the CalARP regulation, to ensure that written procedures and practices were developed, reviewed, implemented, and reflective of current plant practice.

Operating procedures were originally developed in hard copy format as part of the construction contract for the completion of Randall-Bold WTP.  Revisions to the plan have been made over time, the procedures for which are described later in this section.  All operating procedures have been recently been converted to computer format.  They are now available on computer and include the following modes of operation:

¿	Initial startup;
¿	Normal operations;
¿	Temporary operations;
¿	Emergency shutdown;
¿	Emergency operations;
¿	Normal shutdown;
¿	Startup following a normal or emergency shutdown or a major change that requires a hazard review; 
¿	Consequences of deviation and steps required to correct or avoid deviations; and,
¿	Equipment inspections

